Lege Fufia Caninia certus modus constitutus erat in servis testamento manumittendis. quam quasi libertatibus impe· dientem et quodammodo invidam tollendam esse censuimus, cum satis suerat inhumanum vivos quidem licentiam habere totam suam familiam libertate donare, nisi alia causa impediat libertati, morientibus autem huiusmodi licentiam adimere.

The lex Fufia Caninia (Gaius i. 42-46, Ulpium, reg. 1. 24 2 5, Paul. sent. rec. 4. ι4) was passed in the reign os Augustus, about the same time as the lex Aelia Sentia (Suetonius, Octav. 4ο) ; its design was to put a check on the reckless testamentary manumissions by which testatore sought to glorify themselves. lt enacted that in future an owner ol three slaves should be able by will to manumit only, two; os lrom four to ten, only one hall; ol from eleven to thirty, only one third ; ol from thirty-one to one hundred, only a fourth ; and oi from one hun- dred and one to five hundred, only a fifth : but in no case might more than a hundred be enfranchised in this way. The slaves whom the testator wished to manumit must be specified by name (Ulpian, reg. 1. 24), or by some adequate description: ‘nominatim videntur liberi esse iussi, qui vel ex artificio, vel officio, vel quolibet alio modo evidenter denotati essent, veluti dispensator meus, cellarius meus, coquus meus, Pamphili servi mei lilius’ Dig. 40. 4 24, Paul. sent. rec. 4 14. r.

lf the testator attempted to evade the statute by naming more than made up the number permitted, and arranging their names in a circle, liberty was denied them all, ‘quia nullus ordo manumissionis inve· nitur' Gaius i. 46. For Justinian's repeal oi the lex FufiaCaninia see Cod 7. 3.
